Agent Hub Platform – Good vs Bad Problem Statements

Purpose of this Document

This document defines how use case teams should frame problem statements for the Agent Hub platform.

A common anti-pattern is teams requesting generic agents such as:

“QA Agent”

“Software Development Agent”

“BA Agent”

“PO Agent”

“UI Developer Agent”

“Designer Agent”


These labels are too broad and do not describe:

the actual workflow,

the current maturity of the process,

the systems involved,

the expected outcomes,

or measurable success criteria.


Agent Hub works best when the problem statement is:

1. Process-oriented


2. Context-aware


3. Input/output driven


4. Constrained by enterprise standards


5. Measurable through clear success criteria




---

Core Principle

Bad Problem Statement

> “We need a UI Developer Agent.”



This does not explain:

What stage the UI is in

What inputs exist

Whether design assets exist

Which frameworks or libraries are mandatory

What outputs are expected

What success means



---

Good Problem Statement

> “The team has partially implemented a React-based UI and wants to accelerate feature development using Agent Hub. The agent should generate UI components using the organization’s approved component library, adhere to enterprise coding standards, and create associated unit and integration test cases for all generated functionality.”



This is actionable because it defines:

Current state

Desired workflow

Constraints

Technology ecosystem

Expected outputs

Quality expectations



---

Characteristics of a Good Agent Problem Statement

Area	Good Practice

Business Context	Clearly describe current workflow/problem
Inputs	Define artifacts available to the agent
Outputs	Define expected deliverables
Constraints	Mention standards, tools, governance
Human-in-the-loop	Clarify review/approval points
Success Criteria	Include measurable outcomes
Scope Boundaries	Define what the agent should NOT do
Enterprise Alignment	Mention approved libraries/tools/platforms



---

Standard Problem Statement Template

1. Business Problem

Describe the operational challenge or productivity gap.

2. Current State

Explain what exists today.

Examples:

Partial implementation exists

Manual process performed by BA team

Repetitive data-cleaning effort

Jira ticket creation done manually


3. Desired Agent Capability

Describe what the agent should assist with.

4. Inputs Available

Examples:

Existing codebase

Design system

Requirement documents

Jira templates

CSV/Excel files

Sample datasets


5. Expected Outputs

Examples:

Production-ready code

Jira tickets

Test cases

Cleaned datasets

Validation reports


6. Constraints and Governance

Examples:

Must use enterprise component library

Must follow coding standards

Must not deploy directly to production

Must preserve auditability

Must require human approval before publishing


7. Success Criteria

Examples:

Reduced manual effort by 40%

Generated code passes linting and unit tests

Jira tickets follow organization template

Data cleaning accuracy above 95%



---

Example 1 – UI Development Agent

Poor Problem Statement

> “We need a Frontend Development Agent.”



Why This Is Poor

No workflow context

No technology details

No boundaries

No measurable outcomes

No governance constraints



---

Recommended Problem Statement

Business Problem

The frontend team spends significant effort implementing repetitive UI components and associated test cases for enterprise applications.

Current State

The application UI is partially implemented using React. Teams already have:

Existing frontend codebase

Enterprise component library

Coding standards documentation

CI/CD validation process


Developers manually implement remaining screens and create test coverage.

Desired Agent Capability

The Agent Hub solution should assist developers in extending existing UI functionality by:

Generating React components

Reusing approved enterprise UI components

Following organization coding standards

Generating unit and integration test cases

Suggesting accessibility-compliant implementations


Inputs Available

Existing React project

Enterprise component library

Sample implemented screens

API contracts

Design references


Expected Outputs

Production-aligned React components

Test cases

Documentation/comments

Code review recommendations


Constraints

Must use approved component library only

Must comply with ESLint and enterprise standards

Must not introduce unsupported dependencies

Human review required before merge


Success Criteria

30–50% reduction in UI implementation effort

Generated code passes linting checks

Test coverage generated for all new components

Consistent UI adherence across teams



---

Example 2 – BA Requirements to Jira Ticket Agent

Poor Problem Statement

> “We need a BA Agent that creates Jira stories.”



Why This Is Poor

No workflow definition

No structure expectations

No ticket standards

No clarification of human approvals



---

Recommended Problem Statement

Business Problem

Business analysts spend significant manual effort converting requirement documents into standardized Jira user stories and tasks.

Current State

Requirements are documented in:

Confluence

Word documents

Meeting notes

Excel trackers


BA teams manually:

Interpret requirements

Break down features

Create Jira epics/stories/tasks

Write acceptance criteria


This process is time-consuming and inconsistent across teams.

Desired Agent Capability

The Agent Hub solution should assist BAs by:

Parsing requirement documents

Identifying functional features

Generating structured Jira epics/stories/tasks

Creating acceptance criteria

Suggesting dependencies and subtasks

Highlighting ambiguities or missing information


Inputs Available

BRD/FRD documents

Confluence pages

Existing Jira templates

Historical Jira tickets

Agile process guidelines


Expected Outputs

Jira-ready stories/tasks

Acceptance criteria

Story descriptions

Suggested labels/components

Traceability mapping to source requirements


Constraints

Must follow organization Jira templates

Must not auto-publish tickets without approval

Human validation required before backlog creation

Must maintain traceability to source documentation


Success Criteria

Reduced ticket creation effort by 50%

Improved consistency of Jira stories

Reduced ambiguity in acceptance criteria

Faster backlog grooming cycles



